var createCounter = function () {
  var counter = 0;
  return function () {
    counter += 1;
    return counter;
  };
};

var myCounterX = createCounter();
myCounterX();
myCounterX();
console.log(myCounterX());
console.log(counter);

In this example, the value of counter is not available outside of the function, however, when myCounterX is run, and counter is changed....that value is retained, and as long as you are operating withing that returned function. 

Now if we store that return function into another varibale...are there now two instances of counter within two seperate scopes??

the answer is Yes...., two different variables with the same name,
